label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$M$", M, S);
draw(rightanglemark(A,M,B,10));
[/asy] We know that $BM = MC = \frac{BC}{2} = 5.$ Now we just simply apply the Pythagorean Theorem on the right triangle $\triangle ABM.$ \begin{align*}
AM^2 &= AB^2 - BM^2\\
AM^2 &= 8^2 - 5^2 = 39\\
AM &= \boxed{\sqrt{39}}
\end{align*}

problem:
In triangle $ABC$, angle $ACB$ is 50 degrees, and angle $CBA$ is 70 degrees.  Let $D$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $A$ to $BC$, $O$ the center of the circle circumscribed about triangle $ABC$, and $E$ the other end of the diameter which goes through $A$.  Find the angle $DAE$, in degrees.

[asy]

unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, O;

